er nine. Evaluating the Economic Costs and Benefits of Slowing the Spread of Emerald Ash Borer -- tChapter ten. Climate Change Challenges in the Management of Invasive Sea Lamprey in Lake Superior -- tChapter eleven. Ecological Separation without Hydraulic Separation: Engineering Solutions to Control Invasive Common Carp in Australian Rivers -- tChapter twelve. Does Enemy Release Contribute to the Success of Invasive Species? A Review of the Enemy Release Hypothesis -- tSection IV. Where To from Here? Policy Prospects at International, National, and Regional Levels -- tIntroduction -- tChapter thirteen. From Global to Local: Integrating Policy Frameworks for the Prevention and Management of Invasive Species -- tChapter fourteen. Developing Invasive Species Policy for a Major Free Trade Bloc: Challenges and Progress in the European Union -- tChapter fifteen. There Ought to Be a Law! The Peculiar Absence of Broad Federal Harmful Nonindigenous Species Legislation -- tChapter sixteen. Pathways toward a Policy of Preventing New Great Lakes Invasions -- tChapter seventeen. Final Thoughts: Nature and Human Nature -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past several decades, the field of invasion biology has rapidly expanded as global trade and the spread of human populations have increasingly carried animal and plant species across natural barriers that have kept them ecologically separated for millions of years. Because some of these nonnative species thrive in their new homes and harm environments, economies, and human health, the prevention and management of invasive species has become a major policy goal from local to international levels. Yet even though ecological research has led to public conversation and policy recommendations, those recommendations have frequently been ignored, and the efforts to counter invasive species have been largely unsuccessful. Recognizing the need to engage experts across the life, social, and legal sciences as well as the humanities, the editors of this volume have drawn together a wide variety of ecologists, historians, economists, legal scholars, policy makers, and communications scholars, to facilitate a dialogue among these disciplines and understand fully the invasive species phenomenon. Aided by case studies of well-known invasives such as the cane toad of Australia and the emerald ash borer, Asian carp, and sea lampreys that threaten US ecosystems, Invasive Species in a Globalized World offers strategies for developing and implementing anti-invasive policies designed to stop their introduction and spread, and to limit their effects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBiological invasions. 0aIntroduced organisms. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ainvasive species, biology, globalization, habitat, ecosystem, environment, nature, conservation, preservation, nonfiction, science, legal, law, policy, biodiversity, cane toads, australia, squirrels, carp, risk assessment, importation, great lakes, regulation, nonindigenous, legislation, european union, enemy release, sea lamprey, rivers, engineering, lake superior, emerald ash borer, environmental impact, zoology.1 aBennington, Val, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossenbroek, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrammeier, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgiel, Stanley W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCadotte, Marc W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCadotte, Marc W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCadotte, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 